<h1>@HI{{sorenara}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> <strong>@HI{{sorenara}}</strong> ...
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{sorenara}}</strong> is a conjunction used a the beginning of a sentence to refer to something
mentioned in a previous sentence. The meaning is "in that case".

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      A: @HI{{@KJ{{head}}ga@KJ{{pain}}iidesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      B: @HI{{<strong>sorenara</strong>sugu@KJ{{lie*down}}nasai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      A: I have a headache.
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      B: In that case, go to and lie down straightaway.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
The @HI{{sore}} in @HI{{<strong>sorenara</strong>}} refers to something in a previous sentence. The @HI{{nara}} refers to the speaker's supposition regarding the truth of the previous statement.
</p>

<p>
@HI{{<strong>sorenara</strong>}} has a more formal form @HI{{sorenaraba}}.
</p>

<p>
The sentence following @HI{{<strong>sorenara</strong>}} is bound by the same restrictions that apply to @HI{{nara}}.
</p>

<p>
Unlike <a href="grammar-sore-dewa.html">@HI{{soredeha}}</a>, @HI{{<strong>sorenara</strong>}} depends on a verbal context.
/p>

